Env Scientist V AC: General		State of Vermont		Montpelier, VT, US		<div class="rich-text" itemprop="description"><strong>Listing Info<br /><br /></strong>General Information<br />This position,<strong> Environmental Scientist V, (Job Opening # 617503)</strong>, is open to all State employees and external applicants.<br /><br />If you would like more information about this position, please contact Neil Kamman at neil.kamman@vermont.gov .<br /><br />Resumes will not be accepted via e-mail. You must apply online to be considered.<br /><br /><strong>Overview<br /><br /></strong>The Monitoring, Assessment and Planning Program (MAPP) is seeking an energetic individual with high-level water quality modeling and analysis skills to assist the Watershed Management Division’s (WSMD) efforts to implement the Vermont Surface Water Management Strategy. MAPP supports a dynamic and integrative work environment that provides surface water monitoring, assessment, analyses, and watershed management planning services to the regulatory, implementation and planning efforts in the Division and across ANR. The position is primarily dedicated to the development and utilization of water quality models, mechanistic or statistical, aimed at identifying critical source areas of sediment and nutrient pollution. The successful incumbent will be a key player in the implementation of the newly signed Vermont Clean Water Act.<br /><br /><strong>Specific Identified Duties Include<br /></strong><ul><li>Provide water quality and GIS modeling support to the WSMD Monitoring, Assessment and Planning Program for the identification of pollution sources on the landscape.</li><li>Develop or utilize existing water quality models to help characterize water quality conditions, spatially locate potential pollution sources, or predict impacts of remediation actions.</li><li>As appropriate, support MAPP with other GIS/cartographic needs.</li><li>Obtain previously created data layers from within the Agency, or other outside partners.</li><li>Develop new GIS data layers as appropriate.</li><li>Provide modeling and allocation support for TMDL development as needed.</li><li>Produce map products that facilitate the identification of likely pollution sources for inclusion in the Tactical Basin Plans.</li><li>Work with the MAPP Database Manager to explore ways of incorporating WQ data into methodologies for identifying priority implementation areas.</li><li>Assist the WSMD staff responsible for developing/utilizing pollution control “tracking tools”</li><li>Maintain pollution source models and update/improve their capability as new data is developed or becomes available.</li><li>On occasion, participate in ground-truthing investigations with field staff to check accuracy of pollution source identification methods.</li><li>Develop and maintain relationships with other modelers/GIS specialists within ANR and with outside parties (e.g. NRCS, AAFM, USEPA, UVM, VTrans, etc.).<br /><br /></li></ul><strong>Desirable Skills And Qualifications Include<br /></strong><ul><li>Understanding of water quality modeling approaches that may include SWAT, HSPF, WASP, QUAL2x, Basins, Hydrocad, Stella, or other applications, and/or statistical water quality modeling tools.</li><li>Demonstrated skill using geographic information systems, and integrating geographic data with modeling applications.</li><li>A high degree of fluency with computer systems, and a basic understanding of the principals of modern data management and database construction.</li><li>Ability to convey complex models and findings to citizen audiences.<br /><br /></li></ul>General Job Description<br />Scientific work at an advanced professional level for the Department of Environmental Conservation. Duties involve complex tasks in the technical review and analysis of environmental policies, programs, activities and data in a variety of regulatory, non-regulatory, and science programs. Duties entail the collection and analysis of scientific data, evaluation of conceptual plans for scientific investigation, and the preparation, execution and evaluation of scientific studies. Work differs from a lower level scientist in the complexity of assigned responsibilities. Provides expertise in a specialized scientific or program elements, which is not duplicated in the Department. Work is performed under the general direction of a section supervisor or division director.<br /><br />To read the full job specification for this position, please visit DHR Job Specifications .<br /><br /><strong>Education And Experience<br /><br /></strong>Master's degree in biology, microbiology, chemistry, soils science, geology or hydrogeology AND two (2) years or more of experience in environmental biology, microbiology or chemistry, ecology, soils science, geology or hydrogeology.<br /><br />OR<br /><br />Master's degree in any biological-life or physical science AND three (3) years or more of experience in environmental biology, microbiology or chemistry, ecology, soils science, or hydrogeology.<br /><br />OR<br /><br />Bachelor's degree in any biological-life or physical science AND five (5) years or more of professional experience in environmental biology, microbiology or chemistry, ecology, soils science, or hydrogeology.<br /><br />OR<br /><br />Bachelor's degree in biology, microbiology, chemistry, soils science, geology or hydrogeology AND five (5) years or more of professional experience in environmental biology, microbiology or chemistry, or ecology, soils science, geology or hydrogeology.<br /><br />OR<br /><br />One year experience as an Environmental Scientist IV or two years as an Environmental Scientist III.<br /><br /><strong>Special Requirements<br /><br /></strong>n/a<br /><br />Equal Employment Opportunity<br />The State of Vermont is an Equal Opportunity Employer. Applications from women, individuals with disabilities, veterans, and people from diverse cultural backgrounds are encouraged.<br /><br /></div